        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText> We need to reach a 1sigma sensitivity of 15uJy on the continuum in Band 6 to distinguish whether SEDSJ021720.23-050907.5 is a dusty galaxy at z~7 or a post-starburst galaxy at z~8 with more than 3sigma significance. We estimated this sensitivity requirement using several models and empirical SEDs of star-forming and quiescent galaxies (see Figure 5 of Science Justification). 
 We can observe with both Band 6 and 7 because the dust continuum peak of z~7 dusty galaxy redshift around the boundary frequency of Band 6 and 7 (275GHz). However, Band 6 has higher sensitivity than Band 7, which reduces our time request by a factor of two. So we set the four spectral windows in the higher frequency range in Band 6 (256 and 258GHz in LSB, and 272 and 274 in USB with a bandwidth of 2GHz), and set the highest frequency window (Baseband-4: 274GHz) as the representative frequency. 
 We do not need high angular resolution because our target is spatially isolated; depth is the driving factor for our science. So we require the angular resolution of 1.0 arcsec that corresponds to the relatively compact 12m antenna configuration. With this antenna configuration, the 1sigma sensitivity of 15uJy is expected to be achieved with the total observing time of ~3 hours, which we estimated using the OT. 
 Our observing configuration is simple, robust, and will yield a useful scientific result even in the case of a non-detection. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
