    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract> We here propose ALMA follow-up of SEDJ021720.23-050907.5, one of a new population of galaxies with extremely red K - [3.6] color identified in our previous work (Mawatari et al. 2014, in prep). Our SED fitting analysis using very deep photometry from optical to infrared wavelengths (0.4 - 10um) suggested that there are two possibile populations about this object: (1)post-starburst galaxy (age~0.3Gyr, SFR=0, and no dust) at z~8, and (2)star-forming galaxy (obscured by dust; Av=2.5) at z~7. Deep ALMA Band 6 observation for dust continuum will provide the only crue to distinguish if the target galaxy is in post-starburst or dusty star-forming phase. We request 3 hours observing time with Band 6, which can definitively reject the possibility that the target is a dusty star-forming galaxy at z~7. If this object is really a massive quiescent galaxy at z~8, it will be a surprising discovery, because such population of galaxies is expected to be very rare and even one such galaxy has much to say about the history of galaxy formation in the very early universe. </prp:abstract>
